# Dannce Features Dev. Guide

List of features and development suggestions that may help a future developer of the DANNCE GUI. Includes some starting points and recommendations for developers.

Written: January 2025, by Chris Axon

## Allow Users to run DANNCE jobs on local machine (not slurm)

GOAL: Currently users can only run DANNCE/COM train & predict on a Slurm cluster. Would like to allow users to run on local machine. This will allow users without academic cluster to run slurm. Additionally some users (e.g. Kyle) have told me they run DANNCE locally on a consumer GPU (e.g. RTX 4090).

SUGGESTED IMPLEMENTATION:

* Work has been partially completed by changing slurm\_job table to a more generic gpu\_job table.  
* After job submission, lookup runtime by "runtime\_id"  
  * If the runtime\_type is "LOCAL", it is a local job  
  * If the runtime\_type is "SLURM", it is a slurm/cluster job  
* The first stage of job submission can work the same, up until the call to taskqueue.submit\_job.(...).delay()  
* Inside the function: \`submit\_train\_job\` in taskqueue.submit\_job, you should add a branching statement on runtime\_type  
* For slurm jobs, continue as usual  
* For local jobs, define a submission file (similar to a sbatch file) where:  
  * Code will cwd/run from the proper directory  
  * Code will save logs to the LOGS\_DIR  
  * Will config from CONFIG\_DIR  
* Finally, to actually submit the job, I would recommend:  
  * Create an SDANNCE docker image  
  * Use docker sibling containers (i.e. two docker containers running on the same host side-by-side, instead of one container running in the other).  
  * From the DANNCE\_GUI container, start a docker instance of the SDANNCE container with mounting the instance folder and telling it which config file to use  
  * After the process is started, save the docker process/instance ID to the "local\_process\_id" field in the table "gpu\_job". Also update "local\_status" to PROCESSING.  
  * The GUI container can use \`docker ps\` to monitor progress in the SDANNCE container (or multiple running at the same time); when the SDANNCE container finishes, you can update the resources in the host container, similar to what happens with slurm. E.g. update "predictions" table, and "gpu\_job" with STATUS to "COMPLETED", etc.  
* ALTERNATIVELY: you could run SDANNCE in another process on the same container. This is a little easier to set up, but it makes the task less modular.  
  * You need to create a SDANNCE conda environment within the DANNCE\_GUI docker file  
  * When you want to submit a SDANNCE job, use python subprocess to start the task, and monitor it as a local process (e.x. **ps \-p $PIDz**)  
  * If you do this, make sure the GUI docker instance is running with GPU support\!

## Improve Video Preview of Predictions

GOAL: allow for the prediction preview feature, allow the user to stream the video, and overlay skeletons on it. Instead of having to pick "Frames to Preview" and loading still frames from the server. The hard part is making a video overlay, which is compatible with react.

CURRENT IMPLEMENTATION:

![][image2]  
Note: you can also currently load skeletons on top of the video, but it requires going to the settings page and uploading a file.

SUGGESTED IMPLEMENTATION:

* Couple of ways to make annotated skeleton on video:  
  * Look into custom video players which allow annotation; Not sure there is a well maintained library which works well with react, which is also **free/open-source.**  
  * Load an invisible HTML video element, and use a HTML canvas. Every frame, overwrite the canvas using the current frame from the video; then draw the skeleton on the canvas manually.  
  * Use graphics/game library which supports streaming video (not sure if one does). Something like pixi.js. Render the video then use pixijs drawing functions on every frame. Will need to implement behavior such as pause/play and scrolling the video.  
* To stream the video: see function \- **stream\_video\_route** in routes/vdeo\_folder.py  
  * This is used to stream the video for the preview page, similarly can be used to raw video for the prediction preview feature  
* For skeleton data: either download the entire data array before hand (maybe \~100mb \- large but not impossible), or build some sort of streaming endpoint, either mimicking "strea\_video\_route", or with some sort of pagination & pre-loading.

## Improve Table UI's

GOAL: allow user to delete/edit table entries for resource. E.g. video folder name, runtime configurations, predictions, etc. Also, cancel running gpu\_jobs.

CURRENTLY: user cannot edit resources after they're created. This might be ok, since the user can create new resources, but the user should be allowed to delete obsolete resource (e.g. old video data, failed training jobs, etc.)

SUGGESTED IMPLEMENTATION DETAILS:

* On the frontend, place additional Actions in the "Actions" column, e.g. Delete | Edit![][image3]  
* Create routes for each resource on the backend. E.g. 

**\# predictions**  
**@router.delete**("/{id}")  
def delete\_prediction( id: str )  
	...

* These routes will call \`delete from {table}\` statements on the database. BE CAREFUL about dependent tables â€“ if a resource references other resource (e.g. predict\_job references a runtime), you may need to delete all of the referenced resource before deleting the referencing resource.  
  * E.g. predict\_job table has column runtime REFERENCES runtime(id).  
  * If you want to delete the runtime, you first must delete all predict\_job rows which reference the runtime.  
  * Note the ON DELETE behavior in the database sql file: e.g. "ON DELETE CASCADE"
